title: For Sale:  Compact Carry 380 Bersa
postcontent:
Brand: Bersa
 
Caliber: 380
 
Condition: Terrific!
 
 
 
Bersa has beem one of the best defensive pistol bargains on the market for several years now.
 
Top-notch set of features:
 
Double-action/single-action semi-automatic with many similarities to the Walther PPK, famously carried by the fictional secret agent James Bond.
 
Sharp looking green grips.  Upgraded rubber grips for an excellent, sure grip.
 
Slide features a rounded muzzle for easy holstering
 
3-dot sight system and rear cocking serrations.
External controls consist of a slide catch, round magazine release button and combination thumb safety/decocker are placed on the left side of the frame with the takedown lever located on the right side.
 
Safety lever automatically decocks the exposed hammer when it is pressed down into the "Safe" position, resulting in a double-action trigger pull for the first shot. Feels smooth and consistent throughout the arc of travel. After the first shot is fired, the hammer is cocked and ready to operate in single-action mode. Lots of added upgrades usually reserved for more pricey models. The metallic front sight is dovetailed into the slide. The adjustable rear sight has a small screw for windage adjustments instead of being drift adjustable or fixed in place. The top of the slide is checkered to reduce glare.
 
The front and back of the grip frame are grooved for improved purchase as is the face of the trigger.
 
Extended beavertail protects the shooter's hand from hammer bite.
 
The front edge of the roomy trigger guard is curved and textured to act as a finger rest.
 
The magazine release button is deeply checkered for positive operation.
Some little 380s hold just six or seven rounds in the magazine. The Bersa Thunder takes an eight-round magazine that ships with an extended finger rest to ensure a firm three-finger grip. The features, fit and function all add up to a gun that give you plenty of bang for the buck.  
 
Dismantling this pistol is quite simple. Swing and hold the takedown lever down in the 6 o'clock position while pulling back and up on the slide. The rear of the slide lifts off.
 
Handling: the combination of this pistol's smooth, clean trigger, comfortable grip and moderate levels of felt recoil left me wanting more time at the range instead of less.  Slim, light and comfortable on the hip. It feels so well balanced and the grip fits your hands comfortably. It's an ideal option for self-defense practitioners who are new to shooting or those who have been pulling triggers for years.   
 
Utterly reliable! !

Double stack, high capacity magazine.

Unbeatable Taurus lifetime warranty (transferrable to all subsequent owners).

title: For Sale/Trade:  Surplus Rifles, SMLE, M48 Mauser, Type 99 Arisaka
postcontent: I have several surpolus bolt action rifles I'd like to sell, maybe trade.I liked the idea of owning a rifle from each of the major powers during WW2, but now I'm thinking Id rather slim down the rifle calibers in my stable, and just don't think these will be used much.First I have a Lithgow (Australian) made SMLE Mk3, 1941 produced.  Wood has character but is otherwise sound, metal is in good condition.  Barrel is  a bit dark but has excellent rifling and crown.  At one point had a green stripe painted on it for use as a cadet rifle (Green stripe is gtg, yellow or red stripes were not up to mil spec).  Comes with an original Australian produced sword bayonet, handle metal has wear, but blade is good and has a scabbard.  Rifle shoots well and is accurate, but found out after I bought it that the magazine spring is weak and needs replaced.  Have a little bit of ammo and a stripper clip for it as well.Asking $500 or like trade value.Second I have a Type 99 Arisaka in 7.7x58.  I haven't deciphered a lot of the markings, but it is a Nagoya produced rifles, and appears to be an earlier production model with a chromed barrel.  Has provision for monopod and aircraft sights, but they are not present.  Defaced mum.  Mechanically sound but most parts are mismatched.  Wood is in pretty good condition, metal has some wear.  Along with it I have a set of almost new Lee 7.7 Arisaka dies and some 8mm Mauser brass formed to 7.7 Arisaka.Asking $300 for everything.Third I have a Yugo M48 Mauser that I currently have set up in a "Scout" configuration.  Has a scrubbed receiver for export sale, was told it was an "Egyptian Contract" rifle but there is no way to confirm this.  Regardless it is in excellent condition throughout.  Currently equipped with a Bad Ace Tactical scout scope mount (no permanent modifications done, sits in place of the rear sight), with a Vortex 2-7 Scout scope, along with a Voodoo Tactical cheek riser.Will sell this rifle depending on how you want it.$420 for the bare rifle$70 for scout mount$150 for Vortex scope$20 for Voodoo cheek riser$650 for the full package.  Will not sell off the accessories before the rifle is sold.Prefer to sell, but would consider some trades.Primarily interested in American surplus rifles, would work out a combination deal depending on what you have.  Would like a nice Garand, a Springfield 1903 (already have a 1903A3), and in particular I would really like a USGI M1 Carbine (I am NOT interested in modern reproductions or Universal made rifles).  Possibly a Springfield M1A.  Might consider other rifles, but I'm not interested in hunting rifles or shotguns of any kind.  Would consider 1911's or other handguns in 9mm or 45 (no XD's/XDm's), not really interested in anything in 40 unless its a longslide.  Would look at S&W revolvers in .357.  Possibly other things but I'm not desperate to part with these.If interested feel free to call/text three 16 six 19 nine 853, texts preferred.  More pictures on request, can only post three at a time here.Thanks!
